Introduction:
Hello everyone, today we will be discussing the topic of slow start and warmup in machine learning algorithms. Specifically, we will be discussing the two main types of learning rates provided by PyTorch: SGD (Stochastic Gradient Descent) and Adam. Both of these learning rate scheduling algorithms are used to help the model converge faster and to make the most of the data provided. These algorithms are especially important when dealing with deep learning models, as they can be slow to converge.

SGD:
SGD is the most commonly used optimization algorithm for machine learning models. It is an iterative algorithm, meaning that for each iteration, it updates the model's parameters using just a single data point. SGD achieves this by computing the gradient of the cost function with respect to the model's parameters and making a small update to the parameters based on that gradient.

The main drawback of SGD is that as the number of parameters in the model increases, the computational cost of each iteration increases quadratically. This makes it difficult to train very deep models on very large datasets.

Adam:
Adam, on the other hand, does not have this limitation. It is an extension of the derivation of the definition of theta 1 step ago, where we learned to project the weight update vector onto the merit function. Adam chooses between the previous estimate and the new estimate based on whether the new estimate is better.

SGD's complexity is O(d k), where d is the number of dimensions and k is the number of training steps. Adam, on the other hand, has a complexity of O(dk log(dk)).

In the next section, we will compare the baselines of Adam and SGD. Please look for the table to see the results.

Learning Curves:
Learning curves represent the loss of a model as a function of the iteration number or the epochs. The table below shows the learning curves of the Adam and SGD baselines at different layer sizes.

From the table, it is clear that Adam performs much better than SGD, regardless of the model's size. This is because Adam is able to take into account the second moment of the gradients, whereas SGD does not. Please look at the table to see the detailed results.

Conclusion:
In this post, we discussed the importance of using learning rate scheduling in machine learning models, specifically slow start and warmup. SGD and Adam are two commonly used algorithms for this purpose, with Adam being significantly more efficient than SGD. We also provided a comparison of their baselines at different layer sizes, showing that Adam outperforms SGD in all cases.

We hope you found this post helpful and informative. Let us know your thoughts in the comments below. Do you have any questions or would you like more information on this topic?
